During a crisis, time may seem to speed up or slow down, depending on how you feel. Time can be perceived as moving more slowly during stressful situations because of your attention and focus being diverted to the crisis. Additionally, when you are experiencing stress, your body releases hormones that can affect your perception of time. The fight-or-flight response increases heart rate and blood pressure, which can make it feel like time is moving more quickly. This is why it's common to experience a sense of "time flying" during stressful situations.

However, it's important to note that the perception of time is subjective and depends on individual factors such as age, emotions, and experiences. So while it may seem like time is moving faster during a crisis, this is not necessarily true for everyone.

